<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-347-876  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 347 876.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 16 1990 v7 n15 p177(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Judge's order buoys Motorola stock. (federal judge Lucius Buntonpermits Motorola to continue shipping 68030 microprocessor)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Parker, John.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Motorola Inc stock rose four points during the week of Apr 9,1990, as a result of US District Judge Lucius Bunton's decision torescind an injunction that would have required the company to stopshipping its 68030 microprocessor.andP;  The semiconductor firm hadbeen involved in a dispute with Hitachi Ltd over patentinfringement, and Bunton issued an order, on Mar 29, 1990,preventing either company from selling or marketing its chips.andO;The judge later stayed the order because the 68030 is Motorola'sflagship product, and it could cripple many Motorola customers ifthe chip unavailable for a long time.andP;  Investors feared thatHitachi would have the order reinstated, but Bunton has delayedruling on the Hitachi motion until Jun 18.andP;  A strong semiconductormarket is also driving Motorola stock prices upward.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Motorola Inc. (securities).andO;Ticker:    MOT.andO;Product:   Motorola 68030 (Microprocessor) (production control).andO;Topic:     Semiconductor industryStockLaw SuitMarket AnalysisMicroprocessors.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By John ParkerandM;A federal judge's order and a stronger-than-expected semiconductor marketcombined to give Motorola Inc. a boost on Wall Street last week.andM;The Schaumburg, Ill., company's stock, trading at three times its normalvolume, moved up four points to $68.50 a share, despite the report of amodest 3.3 percent increase in first-quarter net income.andP;  The apparentcatalyst was the decision made by U.S.andP;  District Judge Lucius Bunton inAustin, Texas, that permits Motorola to continue shipping its 68030microprocessor.andM;Concerns over a halt in 68030 shipments had investors worried, said JohnGeraghty, an analyst at investor First Boston Corp. in New York.andP;  &quot;If youcan't deliver as a sole source, you're in trouble,&quot; he said.andM;The 68030 is Motorola's flagship microprocessor that has captured industryattention in its long, high-stakes legal contest with Japanese competitorHitachi Ltd.andP;  Hitachi filed suit last June, claiming the 68030 infringes on aHitachi patent for its H8-532 microprocessor.andP;  On March 29, Bunton issued aninjunction preventing either company from selling or marketing their chips.andO;The judge stayed that order the next day, however, allowing Motorola tocontinue shipping pending appeal.andM;Hitachi moved to reinstate the injunction, prompting investors' fears that68030 shipments would be blocked after all.andP;  Bunton said last week, however,that he would delay ruling on that motion until June 18.andP;  Motorola officialssaid last week that they filed an appeal that could keep the whole case incourt for another eight months.andM;The patent-infringement battle snowballed last fall, when Hitachi sued overalleged infringement by Motorola in the design of its 88000 ReducedInstruction Set Computer family.andP;  That suit has yet to go to trial.andM;News of the latest legal decision coincided with the release of Motorola'sfinancial results for the first quarter, ended March 31.andP;  The companyreported that revenue increased to $2.53 billion from $2.17 billion for theyear-ago quarter.andP;  Net income increased 3.3 percent, from $123 million to$127 million.andM;While Motorola officials acknowledged that operating income dropped in theSemiconductor Products Group, sales were up 13 percent and order backlog up17 percent from the first quarter of the previous year.andP;  Geraghty saidinvestors are encouraged about the semiconductor sector.andM;&quot;The inventories are low, and the demand is not bad -- especially at the lowend where Motorola is,&quot; he said.andM;Motorola reported an unspecified decline in income for its InformationSystems Group and flat sales for its Government Electronics Group.andP;  While thecompany did not break out results for its PC systems, analysts said thecompany has yet to turn a profit on those products.andO;</TEXT></DOC>